// Local development only. This file is what makes `gateway/kube` compile against the gateway core in
// YOUR checkout, without a `replace` directive.
//
// The distinction is the whole point, and it cost us a blocker: a `replace` in gateway/kube/go.mod
// applies ONLY to the main module. Inside this repo it works, and every test passes — but a consumer
// running `go get github.com/ConfigButler/krm-stream/gateway/kube` IGNORES it, resolves the core
// module at the literal version in the require line, and fails:
//
//	reading github.com/ConfigButler/krm-stream/gateway/go.mod
//	  at revision gateway/v0.0.0: unknown revision gateway/v0.0.0
//
// Nothing inside this repository could catch that, because the replace hid it from every test we
// have. So the require line now names a REAL, resolvable version of the core module, and this
// go.work — which consumers never see — is what points it back at the working tree for us.
//
// The check that this stays true lives in CI (`a stranger can go get this`), and it deliberately runs
// from a clean module OUTSIDE this workspace, because that is the only place the bug is visible.
go 1.26.0

use (
	./gateway
	./gateway/kube
)
